{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f6630747-7056-4d41-8939-9fe1badc4f8e","content":"PID 12345 isn't running on this machine, so I can't inspect it directly. Here's how to diagnose and configure dumps on **your** system:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Determine the runtime\n\n```bash\n# If CoreCLR, you'll see libcoreclr.so in the process memory maps:\ngrep -q 'libcoreclr' /proc/12345/maps && echo \"CoreCLR\" || echo \"Likely NativeAOT\"\n\n# Double-check — NativeAOT binaries are fully self-contained with no .deps.json:\nls -l /proc/12345/exe   # shows the binary path\nfile $(readlink /proc/12345/exe)   # should say \"statically linked\" for NativeAOT\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2a. CoreCLR crash dumps\n\nSet these **environment variables** (e.g. in your systemd unit or shell):\n\n```bash\n# Enable the built-in CLR dump generation\nexport DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\n\n# Dump type: 1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4\n\n# Where to write dumps (%d = PID, %t = timestamp)\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=\"/tmp/coredumps/core_%d_%t.dmp\"\n\nmkdir -p /tmp/coredumps\n```\n\nAlternatively, use the **kernel core pattern**:\n\n```bash\n# Route all core dumps via kernel\necho '/tmp/coredumps/core.%e.%p.%t' | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2b. NativeAOT crash dumps\n\nNativeAOT does **not** have the `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` mechanism. Use the **kernel core dump** facility instead:\n\n```bash\n# Set kernel core pattern\necho '/tmp/coredumps/core.%e.%p.%t' | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\n\n# Remove the core size limit\nulimit -c unlimited\n\n# For systemd systems that intercept core dumps via coredumpctl:\nsudo mkdir -p /var/lib/systemd/coredump\n# Dumps are then viewable with: coredumpctl list / coredumpctl info\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. Persist across reboots (systemd service example)\n\n```ini\n# In your .service file\n[Service]\nLimitCORE=infinity\n# Add these only for CoreCLR:\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/tmp/coredumps/core_%d.dmp\n```\n\n---\n\n**TL;DR:** Run the `grep libcoreclr` check first. If it's CoreCLR, use the `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` env vars. If it's NativeAOT, use the kernel `core_pattern` + `ulimit -c unlimited`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"81001f80-b9fa-40eb-8b36-47ac7f369061","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The process doesn't exist on this machine. That's expected — the user is asking for help with a process on their own system. Let me give them the diagnostic steps and configuration guidance directly.","outputTokens":830,"requestId":"980C:15E90A:BF5B42:E06DBF:69F407B8"},"id":"105434bb-98dd-44de-9e15-bb0969864ca9","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:54:19.289Z","parentId":"97360239-d266-4cda-8adc-0f25401073cf"}
